This paper examines how race information impacts human decision making in online systems, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of computer science and social sciences. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CY (Computers and Society), which covers research on the social and ethical impacts of computing technology. 

The paper also involves human-computer interaction (HCI) research, as it explores how the presentation of race information affects users' judgments. Therefore, cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) is another likely category. 

The paper also deals with criminal justice and recidivism, which falls under the category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). 

The paper uses machine learning algorithms to predict recidivism, which falls under the category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). 

Finally, the paper involves natural language processing (NLP) techniques to analyze text data, which falls under the category of cs.CL (Computation and Language).
